{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}
{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}
'''William Donald Chapman, Baron Northfield''' known as '''Donald Chapman''', (25 November 1923 &ndash; 18 April 2013)<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201314/ldhansrd/text/130603-0001.htm#13060312000357/ |title=House of Lords announcement 3 June 2013 |publisher=House of Lords Hansard |date= 2013-06-03|accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician.

==Career==
Chapman was educated at [[Barnsley Grammar School]] and [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge]] where he graduated with a degree in economics in 1948. He was the college's senior researcher in agricultural economics from 1943-46.<ref name=ww>{{cite book|title=Who's Who, 2000|publisher=A and C Black|page=1521|isbn=0-7136-5158-X}}</ref>

He took part in local politics in Cambridge town, where he was a member of the [[Cambridge City Council|City Council]] from 1945–47, and concurrent Secretary of Cambridge Trades Council and local Labour Party from 1945 to 1957. Nationally, he was Research Secretary (1948–49) then General Secretary (1949–53) of the [[Fabian Society]].<ref name=ww/>

He was [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Birmingham Northfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Northfield]] from 1951 until he stood down in 1970. He was a Fellow of [[Nuffield College, Oxford]] from 1971 to 1973, Visiting Fellow at the Centre for Contemporary Economics at the [[University of Sussex]] from 1973 to 1979, Chairman of the Rural Development Commission from 1974 to 1980 and Special Adviser to the ECC [[Commission on Environmental Policy]] in 1981.<ref name=ww/>
From 1985 to 1988, he was Director of [[Wembley Stadium]].

After being initially Deputy-Chairman,<ref name=ss2>{{cite news|title=Chief made vision for new town a reality, Tribute to pioneer who created Telford|work=Shropshire Star|date=3 May 2013|page=20}}Report by Toby Neal.</ref> from 1975 to 1987 he was Chairman of the [[Telford Development Corporation]] at a time of extensive development of the [[Telford, Shropshire|Telford]] [[New towns in the United Kingdom|New Town]], in which he demanded better designed [[council housing]] and office developments. He lived during his time in post within the new town, once describing the land within which it was to sit as "21 square miles dominated by a coalfield in final decline".<ref name=ss2/><ref name=ss1>{{cite news|title=News Briefing. Lord Northfield dies at age of 89|work=Shropshire Star|date=3 May 2013|page=1}}</ref> After retirement, he emigrated to [[Hawaii]], U.S.A. but continued to have interest in the area as Chairman of the Maxell Educational Trust which was formed by [[Hitachi Maxell]], one of the industrial companies he encouraged to move into Telford.<ref name=ss2/>

He was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Northfield''', of Telford in the County of [[Shropshire]] on 20 January 1976. Lord Northfield never married and died in [[Honolulu]] aged 89.<ref name=ss2/>

