{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> | name = Dan Balz | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = Dan balz 1910.JPG | image_size = | alt = | caption = reading at the 2014 Gaithersburg Book Festival | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = [[Freeport, Illinois]], U.S. | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = | language = | citizenship = | education = [[Freeport High School (Illinois)|Freeport High School]], | alma_mater = [[University of Illinois]] | period = | genre = Non-fiction | subject = | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = | partner = | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | module = | website = <!-- www.example.com --> | portaldisp = }} '''Daniel Balz''' is an American journalist at ''[[The Washington Post]]'', where he has been a political correspondent since 1978. Balz has served as National Editor, Political Editor, White House correspondent and as the ''Washington Post''{{'}}s [[Texas]]-based Southwest correspondent. Balz sometimes appears on the news show ''[[Meet the Press]]'' and frequently appears on the PBS program ''[[Washington Week]]''. In April 2011 the [[White House Correspondents' Association]] honored Balz with the prestigious Merriman Smith Award for excellence in presidential coverage under deadline pressure.
==Career== {{external media | width = 210px | float= left| headerimage= | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?69485-1/storming-gates ''Booknotes'' interview with Balz on ''Storming the Gates'', February 18, 1996], [[C-SPAN]]}} Balz is co-author, with [[Ronald Brownstein]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', of the 1996 book ''Storming the Gates: Protest Politics and the Republican Revival''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/69485-1/Dan+Balz.aspx|title=Storming the Gates: Interview on C-SPAN|publisher=Booknotes|date=February 18, 1996|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref> In 1999, Balz received the [[American Political Science Association]] award for political coverage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apsanet.org/content_4505.cfm|title=Carey McWilliams Award Winners|publisher=American Political Science Association|date=1999|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref>
Balz's latest work, co-written with [[Pulitzer Prize]] winner [[Haynes Johnson]] in 2009, is ''The Battle for America 2008: The Story of an Extraordinary Election''<ref>{{cite news|last=Balz|first=Dan|last2=Johnson|first2=Haynes|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/31/AR2009073101582.html?hpid=moreheadlines|title=A Political Odyssey: How Obama's Team Forged a Path That Surprised Everyone, Even the Candidate|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=August 2, 2009|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/25776.html|title=Inside 'The Battle for America 2008'|first=Alexander|last=Burns|publisher=Politico|date=August 4, 2009|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2009/08/top-line-spotlight-the-battle-for-america-2008.html|title='Top Line' Spotlight: 'The Battle for America 2008'|website=[[ABCNews.com]]|publisher=ABC News|date=August 7, 2009|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref>. Based on two years of reporting, it includes exclusive interviews with then-candidates [[Barack Obama]] and [[John McCain]] and many of their top advisers during the campaign and election.<ref name="hcc"/>
Before coming to the ''Washington Post'', he worked as a reporter and deputy editor for ''[[National Journal]]''<ref name="hcc">{{cite web|url=http://www.highland.edu/news_events/announcements.asp?newsid=592|title=Dan Balz, National Correspondent for The Washington Post, Keynotes the 2009 Reuben Baumgartner Issues Forum|publisher=Highland Community College|date=August 26, 2009|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref> and as a reporter for the ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''.
==Life== Balz was born in [[Freeport, Illinois]]. A 1964 graduate of Freeport High School, he received bachelor's and master's degrees in communications from the [[University of Illinois]] <ref name="hcc"/> and served in the U.S. Army from 1968 to 1971.<ref name="hcc"/> He is married to Nancy Johnson Balz and they have one son.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/weta/washingtonweek/aroundthetable/balz.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070114205746/http://www.pbs.org/weta/washingtonweek/aroundthetable/balz.html |date=January 14, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dickerson |first=Carole |url=http://www.journalstandard.com/opinions/columnists/x2145962531/You-read-it-here-first |title=You read it here first! |publisher=The Journal-Standard |date=August 18, 2009 |accessdate=2012-06-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930184548/http://www.journalstandard.com/opinions/columnists/x2145962531/You-read-it-here-first |archivedate=2011-09-30 |df= }}</ref>
