{{refimprove|date=March 2018}} {{Infobox company | name = The Cinema Guild| logo = Cinema-guild-logo.png | type = | parent = | owner = | foundation = 1968 | founder = Philip and Mary-Ann Hobel | dissolved = | location = [[New York City|New York, NY]], USA | key_people = | num_employees = | industry = [[Film distribution]]| products = Motion pictures, [[DVD]]s, [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-rays]]| revenue = | operating profit = | homepage = http://www.cinemaguild.com }}
'''The Cinema Guild Inc.''' was established by Philip and Mary-Ann Hobel, producers known for their work in documentaries and features, including the film ''[[Tender Mercies]]''.
Since 1968, the Cinema Guild has been a distributor of both documentary and fiction films (narrative features and shorts), offering distribution in all markets, including educational, non-theatrical, theatrical, television, cable, internet, and home video.
The Cinema Guild launched its own home video brand in March 2009.<ref>http://www.indiewire.com/article/cinema_guild_launches_video_label_to_release_new_yorker_titles/</ref> The company released its first [[Blu-ray]], ''[[Marwencol]]'', in 2011.<ref>http://cinemaguild.com/homevideo/pr_marwencol.htm/</ref>
Internationally acclaimed filmmakers who have released films through the Cinema Guild include [[Claire Denis]], [[Jacques Rivette]], [[Agnès Varda]], [[Pedro Costa]], [[Béla Tarr]], [[Hong Sang-soo]], [[Alexander Sokurov]], and [[Nuri Bilge Ceylan]].
The distributor has also worked with such U.S.-based [[Independent film|independent]] filmmakers as [[Andrew Bujalski]], [[Jem Cohen]], and [[Matthew Porterfield]].
